# **5.3 Git Branching Strategy**

*⚠ The main branch is ALWAYS stable. Never commit directly to main. Every module gets its own branch. Merge only when the module is fully tested.*

| **Item** | **Detail** |
| --- | --- |
| **Repository** | Existing private GitHub repository — jamisan. ERP lives in the erp/ subfolder. |
| **Default branch** | main — production-ready at all times |
| **Module branches** | erp/feature/database-schema, erp/feature/auth-system, erp/feature/order-ingestion, erp/feature/csr-interface, erp/feature/admin-interface, erp/feature/finance-module, erp/feature/reporting-dashboard, erp/feature/wati-integration, erp/feature/polish-deploy |
| **Branch prefix rationale** | erp/ prefix distinguishes ERP branches from other projects (wordpress-plugins, landing-pages) in the same monorepo. |
| **Merge rule** | Pull request to main only when module is tested end-to-end. No direct pushes to main. |
| **Commit message format** | feat: describe what was built. fix: describe what was corrected. docs: spec or README update. |
| **First commit** | SPEC.md committed to main before any code is written. This is the anchor. |

Session ritual — every Claude Code session without exception:

| **Item** | **Detail** |
| --- | --- |
| **Step 1 — Pull** | git pull origin main |
| **Step 2 — Read** | Open SPEC.md. Read fully before touching any code. |
| **Step 3 — Branch** | git checkout feature/[current-module] |
| **Step 4 — Read branch** | Read existing files in the current branch before writing anything new. |
| **Step 5 — Build** | Write code in focused, logical increments. |
| **Step 6 — Commit** | Commit at every meaningful checkpoint with descriptive message. |
| **Step 7 — Test** | Test what was built before ending the session. |
| **Step 8 — Merge** | PR to main only when module is confirmed working. |
| **Step 9 — Review** | End of session: identify any decisions made today not already in spec. Update agenda. |

# **5.4 Environment Variables — .env.example**

*⚠ .env must be in .gitignore and NEVER committed. Use .env.example as the template. On the VPS, set variables via PM2 ecosystem file or system environment, not a committed .env file.*

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# CORE APPLICATION

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

NODE_ENV=development

APP_BASE_URL=https://app.jamisan.com

PORT=3000

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# DATABASE

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

DATABASE_URL=postgresql://username:password@localhost:5432/jamisan_erp

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# SECURITY AND AUTHENTICATION

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

JWT_SECRET=replace_with_256bit_random_string

JWT_EXPIRES_IN=8h

TRUSTED_DEVICE_DAYS=30

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# PABBLY WEBHOOK

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

PABBLY_WEBHOOK_SECRET=replace_with_pabbly_bearer_token

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# GOOGLE SHEETS API — CASH PAID EXPORT

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

GOOGLE_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON=./config/jamisan-erp-service-account.json

GOOGLE_CASH_PAID_SHEET_ID=1BF6y9AnqvLCBtidro_MgnAUxPUHmKGcWcUHrKLx4ExU

GOOGLE_CASH_PAID_TAB_NAME=CashPaid

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# WATI — V2 DIRECT API (not used in V1)

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

WATI_API_TOKEN=replace_with_wati_bearer_token

WATI_TENANT_ID=1052873

WATI_SERVER=https://live-mt-server.wati.io

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# EMAIL NOTIFICATIONS (SMTP)

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

EMAIL_SMTP_HOST=smtp.yourprovider.com

EMAIL_SMTP_PORT=465

EMAIL_SMTP_USER=alerts@jamisan.com

EMAIL_SMTP_PASS=replace_with_smtp_password

EMAIL_FROM_ADDRESS=alerts@jamisan.com

EMAIL_DIRECTOR_ADDRESS=director@jamisan.com

EMAIL_OPS_ADDRESS=ops@jamisan.com

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# BACKUP

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

BACKUP_LOCAL_PATH=/var/backups/jamisan-erp

RCLONE_REMOTE_NAME=gdrive

RCLONE_REMOTE_PATH=Jamisan-CRM-Backups

# **5.5 .gitignore**

# Node

node_modules/

npm-debug.log

yarn-error.log

# Environment and secrets

.env

*.pem

config/*service-account*.json

# OS files

.DS_Store

Thumbs.db

# Logs

logs/

*.log

# Build artefacts

dist/

.cache/

*ℹ Note: config/*service-account*.json catches the Google service account file regardless of exact filename. More reliable than hardcoding the filename in .gitignore.*

# **5.6 MCP Server Configuration**

Three MCP servers must be active in Claude Code for the Build Blitz. These give Claude Code direct database access and deep context persistence across sessions.

| **Item** | **Detail** |
| --- | --- |
| **Context7** | Maintains UI/UX rules and RBAC roles across all 9 modules. Prevents hallucinating permissions or interface patterns mid-session. |
| **Sequential Thinking** | Enforces step-by-step logic for complex financial routing — trigger rollbacks, variance routing, commission retroactive calculations. |
| **PostgreSQL MCP** | Direct database connection. Claude Code can run schema SQL, test trigger firing, verify seed data, and query live data during build sessions. |
| **Connection string** | postgresql://localhost/jamisan_erp — placeholder until VPS database is created in Module 1. Update after VPS setup. |

# **5.7 VPS Deployment Target**

| **Item** | **Detail** |
| --- | --- |
| **VPS provider** | Hetzner Cloud — CPX32 plan (4 vCPU AMD EPYC, 8 GB RAM, 80 GB NVMe SSD, 20 TB traffic). Finland datacenter. Separate from Bluehost which hosts sales websites. |
| **CDN and security** | Cloudflare — sits in front of VPS. Handles caching, DDoS protection, and bot filtering. All traffic enters via Cloudflare. |
| **Nginx** | Reverse proxy on VPS. Receives traffic from Cloudflare on ports 80 and 443. Handles SSL termination. Routes to Node.js on port 3000 internally. |
| **Node process** | PM2 — keeps Express running continuously. Auto-restarts on crash or server reboot. Cluster mode optional for V2 scaling. |
| **PostgreSQL** | Runs natively on VPS. Secured behind firewall — accessible ONLY to localhost (the Node app). No public PostgreSQL port. |
| **Domain** | app.jamisan.com — subdomain of existing jamisan.com domain. DNS A record points to VPS IP via Cloudflare proxy. |
| **SSL** | Let's Encrypt certificate managed by Certbot on Nginx. Auto-renews every 90 days. |
| **Backup** | pg_dump runs every 6 hours via cron. Stored locally at BACKUP_LOCAL_PATH. rclone pushes daily snapshot to Google Drive. Backup failure triggers email alert to Director. |

# **5.8 SPEC.md — Master Reference File**

SPEC.md lives in the repository root and is the FIRST file Claude Code reads at the start of every session without exception. It is a concise operational reference — not a full spec dump. Links to the full spec documents for deep detail.

*⚠ SPEC.md is committed to main BEFORE any code is written. It is the anchor of the entire Build Blitz. Every Claude Code session opens this file first.*

| **Item** | **Detail** |
| --- | --- |
| **Contents** | Project overview, current build status, tech stack, database summary, session ritual, module list with branch names, key decisions quick reference, links to full spec documents. |
| **Length target** | Readable in under 2 minutes. Maximum 200 lines. Not a copy of the Day 1-4 documents. |
| **Updates** | Updated at the end of every build session when new decisions are made. Say 'update the agenda' to trigger regeneration. |
| **Format** | Markdown. GitHub renders it cleanly. Claude Code reads it natively. |
| **Critical rule** | No Claude Code session proceeds without reading SPEC.md first. This prevents context drift across sessions. |

SPEC.md is generated as a separate file alongside this document. See Jamisan_ERP_SPEC.md in the outputs folder.

